ng 1104","1175":"1175","about 1132":"omkring 1132","about 1133":"omkring 1133","England":"England","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"about 1104–":"circa 1104–Overleden","1100–Male":"1100–Overleden","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1104–Female":"1104–Overleden","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1104":"1104","1133":"1133","1100":"1100","about 1104":"circa 1104","1175":"1175","about 1132":"circa 1132","about 1133":"circa 1133","England":"England","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1104–":"about 1104–Deceased","1100–Male":"1100–Deceased","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1104–Female":"1104–Deceased","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1104":"1104","1133":"1133","1100":"1100","about 1104":"about 1104","1175":"1175","about 1132":"about 1132","about 1133":"about 1133","England":"England","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"HOTHAM","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire): habitational name usually from Hotham (East Yorkshire), but occasionally perhaps also from Holtham in Legsby (Lincolnshire). The East Yorkshire placename may derive from Old English <i>hōdum</i>, dative plural form of <i>hōd</i> ‘shelter’, while the origin of the Lincolnshire placename is uncertain. Compare   Holtham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Holtham","meanings":["English:","habitational name from a place so named or a topographic name for someone who lived ‘(at the) enclosure in the wood’, from Middle English <i>holt</i> ‘wood, grove’ + <i>ham</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>holt</i> + <i>hamm</i>). Compare   Haltom   and   Holtom  .","variant of   Hotham  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":2,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705187,"age":111,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William de HOTHAM was born about 1104, in England. She married William de Hotham about 1132, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1104–":"umbes 1104–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1104–Female":"1104–Surnud","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1104":"1104","1133":"1133","1100":"1100","about 1104":"umbes 1104","1175":"1175","about 1132":"umbes 1132","about 1133":"umbes 1133","England":"England","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1104–":"noin 1104–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1104–Female":"1104–Kuollut","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1104":"1104","1133":"1133","1100":"1100","about 1104":"noin 1104","1175":"1175","about 1132":"noin 1132","about 1133":"noin 1133","England":"England","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1104–":"environ 1104–Décédée","1100–Male":"1100–Décédé","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1104–Female":"1104–Décédée","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1104":"1104","1133":"1133","1100":"1100","about 1104":"environ 1104","1175":"1175","about 1132":"environ 1132","about 1133":"environ 1133","England":"Angleterre","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. William de HOTHAM est née environ 1104, à Angleterre. Elle a épousé William de Hotham environ 1132, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"about 1104–":"um 1104–Verstorben","1100–Male":"1100–Verstorben","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1104–Female":"1104–Verstorben","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1104":"1104","1133":"1133","1100":"1100","about 1104":"um 1104","1175":"1175","about 1132":"um 1132","about 1133":"um 1133","England":"England","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Yorkshire, England","lifeSummary":"Mrs. William de HOTHAM wurde um 1104 in England geboren. Sie hat um 1132 in England William de Hotham geheiratet. Sie hatten mindesten